Sure, here's an example code snippet showing how you can write a unit test using JUnit to test the insertion and retrieval of data from a `Student` model class using Hibernate:

```java
import org.junit.*;
import static org.junit.Assert.*;

public class StudentDaoTest {

    private StudentDao studentDao; // Assume you have a StudentDao class to interact with the database

    @Before
    public void setUp() {
        // Set up the test environment (initialize Hibernate configuration, session factory, etc.)
        // Initialize the StudentDao instance
        studentDao = new StudentDao();
    }

    @Test
    public void testInsertAndRetrieveStudent() {
        // Create a sample student
        Student student = new Student();
        student.setName("John Doe");
        student.setAge(20);
        student.setGrade("A");

        // Insert the student into the database using the StudentDao
        studentDao.insert(student);

        // Retrieve the student using the StudentDao
        Student retrievedStudent = studentDao.getById(student.getId());

        // Perform assertions to validate the retrieved student
        assertNotNull(retrievedStudent);
        assertEquals("John Doe", retrievedStudent.getName());
        assertEquals(20, retrievedStudent.getAge());
        assertEquals("A", retrievedStudent.getGrade());
    }

    @After
    public void tearDown() {
        // Clean up resources and close any open database connections
    }
}
```

In this example, the `setUp` method is annotated with `@Before` to set up the test environment. You would typically initialize the Hibernate configuration, session factory, database connection, or any other necessary components.

The `testInsertAndRetrieveStudent` method is annotated with `@Test` and performs the actual test. It creates a sample `Student` object, inserts it into the database using `studentDao.insert()`, retrieves the student using `studentDao.getById()`, and performs assertions to verify that the retrieved student matches the expected values.

Finally, the `tearDown` method is annotated with `@After` and is responsible for cleaning up any resources, such as closing database connections, that were opened during the test.

Remember to adapt the code according to your specific implementation, such as replacing `StudentDao` with your actual DAO class and adjusting the assertions to match your data model and requirements.
